up to 21 days upon a determination of good cause.
HB228 INTRODUCED
113 (3) A pretrial detention hearing may be continued
114 beyond 21 days on a joint motion of the parties.
115 (4) The defendant shall be detained until the pretrial
116 detention hearing is held and during any continuance unless
117 the court is notified of an agreement of the parties to
118 conditions of bail.
119 (5) If the last day to hold a pretrial detention
120 hearing falls on a Saturday, Sunday, legal holiday, or any
121 other day a court is closed, the hearing shall be set on the
122 following business day.
123 (4)a.(e)(1) A defendant shall have all of the following
124 rights at a pretrial detention hearing:
125 1.a. To be represented by counsel. If the defendant is
126 financially unable to obtain counsel, he or she shall have
127 counsel appointed.
128 2.b. To testify.
129 3.c. To present witnesses.
130 4.d. To present evidence.
131 5.e. To cross-examine witnesses.
132 b.(2) The judge shall have discretion as to who the
133 defendant may call as a witness as provided in this
134 subdivision at the pretrial detention hearing.
135 (5)(f) In considering whether there are any conditions
136 or combination of conditions that would reasonably ensure the
137 defendant's appearance in court or protect the safety of the
138 community and of any person, the court shall consider all of
139 the following factors:
140 a.(1) The nature and circumstances of the offenses
Page 5

a.(1) The nature and circumstances of the offenses
HB228 INTRODUCED
141 charged.
142 b.(2) The weight of the evidence against the defendant.
143 c.(3) The history and characteristics of the defendant,
144 including, but not limited to, the defendant's character,
145 physical and mental condition, family ties, employment,
146 financial resources, length of residence in the community,
147 community ties, past conduct, history relating to drug or
148 alcohol abuse, criminal history, and the defendant's record
149 concerning appearance at court proceedings, and whether, at
150 the time of the current offense, the defendant was on
151 probation, parole, or on other release pending trial,
152 sentencing, appeal, or completion of sentence for an offense.
153 d.(4) The nature and seriousness of the danger to any
154 person or the community if the defendant is released.
155 (6)(g) At any pretrial detention hearing, the rules
156 governing admissibility of evidence in criminal trials shall
157 not apply, and the court shall receive all relevant evidence.
158 All evidence shall be recorded. The testimony of a defendant
159 may not be admissible in any other criminal proceeding against
160 the defendant, except if being used for perjury based on the
161 testimony or for the purpose of impeachment in any subsequent
162 proceeding.
163 (h) A recording of a pretrial detention hearing shall
164 be kept by stenographic reporting, by mechanical or electronic
165 device or by some combination thereof, for the purpose of
166 creating an official record of the proceedings. The audio or
167 stenographic recording shall be preserved until the time for
168 making an appeal has expired. The trial court shall determine
Page 6

making an appeal has expired. The trial court shall determine
